  "texts": [
    "The tensor z m encompasses all points in the Cartesian space, encapsulating all possible permutations of acoustic, textual, and visual modalities.",
    "The process is shown in Figure 2.The individual modality features are represented by f a f t f v, while the sections, z a ⊗ z t, z a ⊗ z v, and z t ⊗ z v, denote the pairwise intermodal interactions.",
    "Prior to the outer product operation, an expansion of dimensions is required, as shown by the section, z a ⊗ z t ⊗ z v, which signifies the interaction among all three modalities.The augmentation process for any two modalities prior to the outer product is as follows: z m =   z ′ v z ′ t z ′ a   =   f v ⊗ 1 f t ⊗ 1 f a ⊗ 1   (2)This expansion allows for the computation of correlations between modalities and preserves intrinsic information within each modality.",
    "Tucker decompositionDue to the high dimensionality of z m resulting from the outer product of three vectors, substantial computational resources are required.",
    "Tucker decomposition, akin to a higher-order Principal Component Analysis (PCA), addresses this by decomposing a high-dimensional tensor into a core tensor G and a set of factor matrices A (1), A (2), A (3),...:z m = G × 1 A (1) × 2 A (2) × 3 A (3)(3)where × n denotes the n-mode product."
